{"title_page": "Bhatoora", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Bhatoora\n| image            = Bhatura.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          =\n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = [[Indian subcontinent]]\n| region           = Northern regions of the Indian subcontinent\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]]\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = White [[flour]] (''maida''), [[dahi (curd)|dahi]] (yogurt), ''[[ghee]]'' or oil, yeast\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n'''Bhatoora''' (also known as '''Batoora''', '''Bhatura''', '''Batura''', '''Pathora''' or [[Puri (food)|puri]]) ({{lang-hi|\u092d\u091f\u0942\u0930\u093e}}, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0628\u06be\u0679\u0648\u0631\u0627}}}}, {{lang-pa|\u0a2d\u0a1f\u0a42\u0a30\u0a3e}}) is a fluffy [[Deep fry|deep-fried]] [[Leavening agent|leavened]] bread originating from the [[Indian subcontinent]]. Variations include ''aloo bhatura'' (bhatura filled with potato) and paneer bhatura (bhatura filled with cottage cheese). It is often eaten with [[chickpea]] [[curry]], ''[[chana masala|chole]]'' or ''channe'', making the traditional dish ''[[chole bhature]]''.\n\nThis bread is like the [[Puri (food)|puri]] bread but is made with leavened dough.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ramineni |first=Shubhra |title=Entice With Spice: Easy Indian Recipes for Busy People |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LpXTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT206}}</ref>\n\n==Ingredients==\nA typical recipe includes white [[flour]] (''maida''), [[dahi (curd)|dahi]] (yogurt), lots of'' [[ghee]]'' or oil, and either [[yeast]] or baking powder. Once kneaded well, the dough is left to rise, and then small balls of this dough are either hand-rolled or flattened using a rolling pin. The bread pieces are then deep fried until they puff up into a lightly browned, soft, fluffy bread, which is elastic and chewy.\nThey are known as Bhatura or Puri, Bhature is served more with chickpeas.\nIf you want complete and accurate information about making chickpea vegetable and bhatura. So you can get complete information by going here. About chole bhature<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.kgrnews.com/resipe/chole-bhature-recipe-chana-bhatura/|title=( \u0361\u0298 \u035c\u0296 \u0361\u0298) chole bhature recipe{{!}}Chana Bhatura{{!}}Puri (food) bikanervala|last=poona|date=2020-03-31|website=kgr news|language=en-US|access-date=2020-04-02}}</ref> Recipe\n\nA nonfried variant is the ''[[kulcha]]'', which can be baked or cooked on a flat pan and is garnished with coriander leaves. It is cooked from the same dough.\n<ref></ref>\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Chana masala]]''\n*[[Punjabi cuisine]]\n*[[Puri (food)|''Puri'']]\n*''[[Paratha]]''\n*''[[Roti]]''\n*''[[Naan]]''\n*''[[Kulcha]]''\n*[[List of Indian breads]]\n*[[List of Pakistani breads]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n*[http://www.sonzyskitchen.com/bhatura.htm ''Bhatura'' recipe]\n*[http://vegika.com/instant-bhatura-with-soda-water-instant-bhatura-recipe-with-soda-water/ ''Bhatura'' recipe]\n*http://www.tarladalal.com/Chole-Bhature-2810r\n\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{Doughnut}}\n\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n\n\n{{india-cuisine-stub}}\n{{bread-stub}}\n{{Breakfast-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Bhatoora\n| image            = Bhatura.jpg\n| image_size       = 250px\n| caption          =\n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = [[Indian subcontinent]]\n| region           = Northern regions of the Indian subcontinent\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]]\n| creator          =\n| course           =\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = White [[flour]] (''maida''), [[dahi (curd)|dahi]] (yogurt), ''[[ghee]]'' or oil, yeast\n| variations       =\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n'''Bhatoora''' (also known as '''Batoora''', '''Bhatura''', '''Batura''', '''Pathora''' or [[Puri (food)|puri]]) ({{lang-hi|\u092d\u091f\u0942\u0930\u093e}}, {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u0628\u06be\u0679\u0648\u0631\u0627}}}}, {{lang-pa|\u0a2d\u0a1f\u0a42\u0a30\u0a3e}}) is a fluffy [[Deep fry|deep-fried]] [[Leavening agent|leavened]] bread originating from the [[Indian subcontinent]]. Variations include ''aloo bhatura'' (bhatura filled with potato) and paneer bhatura (bhatura filled with cottage cheese). It is often eaten with [[chickpea]] [[curry]], ''[[chana masala|chole]]'' or ''channe'', making the traditional dish ''[[chole bhature]]''.\n\nThis bread is like the [[Puri (food)|puri]] bread but is made with leavened dough.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ramineni |first=Shubhra |title=Entice With Spice: Easy Indian Recipes for Busy People |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LpXTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT206}}</ref>\n\n==Ingredients==\nA typical recipe includes white [[flour]] (''maida''), [[dahi (curd)|dahi]] (yogurt), lots of'' [[ghee]]'' or oil, and either [[yeast]] or baking powder. Once kneaded well, the dough is left to rise, and then small balls of this dough are either hand-rolled or flattened using a rolling pin. The bread pieces are then deep fried until they puff up into a lightly browned, soft, fluffy bread, which is elastic and chewy.\n\nA nonfried variant is the ''[[kulcha]]'', which can be baked or cooked on a flat pan and is garnished with coriander leaves. It is cooked from the same dough.\n\n==See also==\n*''[[Chana masala]]''\n*[[Punjabi cuisine]]\n*[[Puri (food)|''Puri'']]\n*''[[Paratha]]''\n*''[[Roti]]''\n*''[[Naan]]''\n*''[[Kulcha]]''\n*[[List of Indian breads]]\n*[[List of Pakistani breads]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{cookbook}}\n*[http://www.sonzyskitchen.com/bhatura.htm ''Bhatura'' recipe]\n*[http://vegika.com/instant-bhatura-with-soda-water-instant-bhatura-recipe-with-soda-water/ ''Bhatura'' recipe]\n*http://www.tarladalal.com/Chole-Bhature-2810r\n\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{Doughnut}}\n\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n\n\n{{india-cuisine-stub}}\n{{bread-stub}}\n{{Breakfast-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Vijay kumar pg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(They are known as Bhatura or Puri, Bhature is served more with chickpeas. If you want complete and accurate information about making chickpea vegetable and bhatura. So you can get complete information by going here. About Chole Bhatur Recipe)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bhatoora"}
{"title_page": "Vijeta (1982 film)", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Vijeta 1983\n| image          =Vijeta_poster.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Govind Nihlani]]\n| producer       = [[Shashi Kapoor]]\n| writer         = [[Dilip Chitre]]<br>\t[[Satyadev Dubey]]\t \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Shashi Kapoor]]<br> [[Rekha]]<br> [[Amrish Puri]]<br> [[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]]<br> [[Supriya Pathak]]<br> [[Om Puri]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br>[[Ajit Varman]]<br>'''Background Score:'''<br>[[Ajit Varman]]\n| cinematography = Govind Nihlani\n| editing        = Keshav Naidu\n| distributor    = Film-valas International\n| released       = March 04, 1982(India)\n| runtime        = 151 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n| website        =\n}}\n'''''Vijeta''''' (English: The Victor) is a [[Bollywood films of 1982|1982]] Indian [[coming-of-age]] Hindi film produced by [[Shashi Kapoor]] and directed by [[Govind Nihalani]]. It stars Shashi Kapoor, his son [[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]], [[Rekha]], [[Amrish Puri]] and [[Supriya Pathak]] with K.K. Raina, Raja Bundela and [[Shafi Inamdar]], who went on to become notable supporting actors in Bollywood movies.\n\n==Plot==\nAngad (Kunal Kapoor) is a confused teenager trying to find himself and is caught in between the marital problems of his Maharashtrian mother Neelima (Rekha) and Punjabi father Nihal (Shashi Kapoor), it is time for him to decide what he wants to do with his life. Angad chooses to become a fighter pilot with the [[Indian Air Force]]. What follows is his struggle to become a victor both with his self and the outer world. Angad is attracted to Anna Verghese (Supriya Pathak), who is the daughter of his flying instructor Group Captain Varghese (Amrish Puri) a [[Malayali]] [[https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Saint_Thomas_Christians|Syrian Christian]]. Angad must learn to adapt to flying, leaving his mom and dad for long periods of time, as well as try and woo Anna who helps him overcome his fears and realize his potential as a fighter pilot. Nihal is a clean-shaven Sikh, Neelima is a Hindu, Angad is a [[Sikh]] and Anna a [[Christians|Christian]], while Angad's fellow officers represent all religions.\n\nThe film is notable for some rarely seen aerial photography of combat aircraft active with the IAF in the 1980s. The central character of Angad is a [[MiG-21]] pilot and is shown flying the aircraft in the ground attack role in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]. Much of the movie, including the climax involving a [[MiG-21]]bis, was shot at Pune. The [[Indian Air Force|IAF]] No.4 Squadron (the '[[Oorials]]') provided the pilots and planes for the film's aerial sequences. The movie included good color footage of the Oorials aircraft in flight and in operation.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shashi Kapoor]] as Nihal Singh\n*[[Rekha]] as Neelima Singh\n*[[Supriya Pathak]] as Anna Varghese\n*[[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]] as Angad\n*[[Amrish Puri]] as [[Group Captain (rank)|Group Captain]] Varghese, the Chief Instructor\n*[[Om Puri]] as Arvind\n*[[Dina Pathak]] as Angad's grandmother (Biji)\n*[[Shafi Inamdar]] as [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Parulkar\n*[[Sulabha Deshpande]]\n*[[Capt Anup Ghosh]] as [[Squadron Leader (rank)|Squadron Leader]]\n\n==Music==\n#\"Bichhurat Mose Kanha\" - [[Parveen Sultana]]\n#\"Man Aanand Aanand Chhaayo\" - [[Asha Bhosle]], Satyasheel Deshpande\n#\"Man Base Mor Brindaban Ma\" - [[Manna Dey]]\n\n==Facts==\n\n* The \"senior pilots of the Indian Air Force\" who are credited with providing assistance with the aerial photography were drawn from No. 4 Squadron, IAF (\"The Fighting Oorials\"). It was their MIG-21Bis' that were used in the aerial combat sequences and much of the film was shot at their then base in Poona/Pune.<ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0153545/trivia Vijeta (1982) - Trivia - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* The I.N.S. Mysore seen in the film was a WW2 British Fiji Class Cruiser, H.M.S. Nigeria that was sold to the Indian Navy in 1957. The ship was decommissioned soon after the film was completed. The current (2006) I.N.S. Mysore is a newer vessel.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n* The aircraft that the pilots train on are domestically produced HAL HJT-16 Kirans.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Filming locations==\n\n* [[Air Force Academy]], [[Dundigal]], [[Hyderabad]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], India\n* Air Force Station, Pune, Maharashtra, India\n* National Defence Academy, Khadakswala, Pune, Maharashtra, India\n* R.K. Studios, Chembur, Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n\n==Reception==\n''Film World'' magazine rated the film \"Good\" and wrote, \"''Vijeta'' is perhaps the first film of its kind, a film which shows the Indian Air Force, its gallant men and their life in true colours.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Film World|volume=20|year=1983|publisher=T.M. Ramachandran}}</ref> According to ''[[Asiaweek]]'', \"''Vijeta'' is a tribute to the IAF in celebration of its golden jubilee last year\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Tribute to a Proud Force|journal=[[Asiaweek]]|publisher=Asiaweek Ltd|volume=9|year=1983|author=C.B. Rao}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Filmfare Best Cinematographer Award]] - Govind Nihalani\n*[[Filmfare Best Editing Award]] - Keshav Naidu<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Editor Award| url = http://recipeguide.indiatimes.com/awards2001/ex_editor.htm |date= |publisher=Official Listings, [[Indiatimes]] | accessdate = 2014-04-29 }}</ref>\n*[[Filmfare Best Sound Award]] - Hitendra Ghosh\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tactics and Air Combat and Defence Establishment]]\n*[[College of Air Warfare]]\n*[[Topgun]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0153545}}\n\n{{Govind Nihalani}}\n\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:Indian aviation films]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian war films]]\n[[Category:Indian coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ajit Varman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Govind Nihalani]]\n[[Category:Indian Army in films]]\n[[Category:Indian Air Force in films]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Military of Pakistan in films]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=November 2015}}\n{{Infobox film\n| name           = Vijeta 1983\n| image          =Vijeta_poster.jpg\n| image_size     =\n| caption        =\n| director       = [[Govind Nihlani]]\n| producer       = [[Shashi Kapoor]]\n| writer         = [[Dilip Chitre]]<br>\t[[Satyadev Dubey]]\t \n| narrator       =\n| starring       = [[Shashi Kapoor]]<br> [[Rekha]]<br> [[Amrish Puri]]<br> [[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]]<br> [[Supriya Pathak]]<br> [[Om Puri]]\n| music          = '''Songs:'''<br>[[Ajit Varman]]<br>'''Background Score:'''<br>[[Ajit Varman]]\n| cinematography = Govind Nihlani\n| editing        = Keshav Naidu\n| distributor    = Film-valas International\n| released       = March 04, 1982(India)\n| runtime        = 151 minutes\n| country        = India\n| language       = Hindi\n| budget         =\n| preceded_by    =\n| followed_by    =\n| website        =\n}}\n'''''Vijeta''''' (English: The Victor) is a [[Bollywood films of 1982|1982]] Indian [[coming-of-age]] Hindi film produced by [[Shashi Kapoor]] and directed by [[Govind Nihalani]]. It stars Shashi Kapoor, his son [[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]], [[Rekha]], [[Amrish Puri]] and [[Supriya Pathak]] with K.K. Raina, Raja Bundela and [[Shafi Inamdar]], who went on to become notable supporting actors in Bollywood movies.\n\n==Plot==\nAngad (Kunal Kapoor) is a confused teenager trying to find himself and is caught in between the marital problems of his Maharashtrian mother Neelima (Rekha) and Punjabi father Nihal (Shashi Kapoor), it is time for him to decide what he wants to do with his life. Angad chooses to become a fighter pilot with the [[Indian Air Force]]. What follows is his struggle to become a victor both with his self and the outer world. Angad is attracted to Anna Verghese (Supriya Pathak), who is the daughter of his flying instructor (Amrish Puri). Angad must learn to adapt to flying, leaving his mom and dad for long periods of time, as well as try and woo Anna who helps him overcome his fears and realize his potential as a fighter pilot. Nihal is a clean shaven Sikh, Neelima is a Hindu, Angad is a [[Sikh]] and Anna a [[Christians|Christian]], while Angad's fellow officers represent all religions.\n\nThe film is notable for some rarely seen aerial photography of combat aircraft active with the IAF in 1980s. The central character of Angad is a [[MiG-21]] pilot and is shown flying the aircraft in ground attack role in the [[Indo-Pakistani War of 1971]]. Much of the movie, including the climax involving a [[MiG-21]]bis, was shot at Pune. The [[Indian Air Force|IAF]] No.4 Squadron (the '[[Oorials]]') provided the pilots and planes for the film's aerial sequences. The movie included good color footage of the Oorials aircraft in flight and in operation.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Shashi Kapoor]] as Nihal Singh\n*[[Rekha]] as Neelima Singh\n*[[Supriya Pathak]] as Anna Verghese\n*[[Kunal Kapoor (Kapoor family)|Kunal Kapoor]] as Angad\n*[[Amrish Puri]] as [[Group Captain (rank)|Group Captain]] Verghese, the Chief Instructor\n*[[Om Puri]] as Arvind\n*[[Dina Pathak]] as Angad's grandmother (Biji)\n*[[Shafi Inamdar]] as [[Wing commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] Parulkar\n*[[Sulabha Deshpande]]\n*[[Capt Anup Ghosh]] as [[Squadron Leader (rank)|Squadron Leader]]\n\n==Music==\n#\"Bichhurat Mose Kanha\" - [[Parveen Sultana]]\n#\"Man Aanand Aanand Chhaayo\" - [[Asha Bhosle]], Satyasheel Deshpande\n#\"Man Base Mor Brindaban Ma\" - [[Manna Dey]]\n\n==Facts==\n\n* The \"senior pilots of the Indian Air Force\" who are credited with providing assistance with the aerial photography were drawn from No. 4 Squadron, IAF (\"The Fighting Oorials\"). It was their MIG-21Bis' that were used in the aerial combat sequences and much of the film was shot at their then base in Poona/Pune.<ref name=autogenerated1>[https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0153545/trivia Vijeta (1982) - Trivia - IMDb<!-- Bot generated title -->]</ref>\n* The I.N.S. Mysore seen in the film was a WW2 British Fiji Class Cruiser, H.M.S. Nigeria that was sold to the Indian Navy in 1957. The ship was decommissioned soon after the film was completed. The current (2006) I.N.S. Mysore is a newer vessel.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n* The aircraft that the pilots train on are domestically produced HAL HJT-16 Kirans.<ref name=autogenerated1 />\n\n==Filming locations==\n\n* [[Air Force Academy]], [[Dundigal]], [[Hyderabad]], [[Andhra Pradesh]], India\n* Air Force Station, Pune, Maharashtra, India\n* National Defence Academy, Khadakswala, Pune, Maharashtra, India\n* R.K. Studios, Chembur, Mumbai, Maharashtra, India\n\n==Reception==\n''Film World'' magazine rated the film \"Good\" and wrote, \"''Vijeta'' is perhaps the first film of its kind, a film which shows the Indian Air Force, its gallant men and their life in true colours.\"<ref>{{cite journal|journal=Film World|volume=20|year=1983|publisher=T.M. Ramachandran}}</ref> According to ''[[Asiaweek]]'', \"''Vijeta'' is a tribute to the IAF in celebration of its golden jubilee last year\".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Tribute to a Proud Force|journal=[[Asiaweek]]|publisher=Asiaweek Ltd|volume=9|year=1983|author=C.B. Rao}}</ref>\n\n==Awards==\n*[[Filmfare Best Cinematographer Award]] - Govind Nihalani\n*[[Filmfare Best Editing Award]] - Keshav Naidu<ref>{{cite web |title=Best Editor Award| url = http://recipeguide.indiatimes.com/awards2001/ex_editor.htm |date= |publisher=Official Listings, [[Indiatimes]] | accessdate = 2014-04-29 }}</ref>\n*[[Filmfare Best Sound Award]] - Hitendra Ghosh\n\n==See also==\n*[[Tactics and Air Combat and Defence Establishment]]\n*[[College of Air Warfare]]\n*[[Topgun]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb title|id=0153545}}\n\n{{Govind Nihalani}}\n\n[[Category:1983 films]]\n[[Category:Indian aviation films]]\n[[Category:1980s Hindi-language films]]\n[[Category:Indian films]]\n[[Category:Indian war films]]\n[[Category:Indian coming-of-age films]]\n[[Category:Films scored by Ajit Varman]]\n[[Category:Films directed by Govind Nihalani]]\n[[Category:Indian Army in films]]\n[[Category:Indian Air Force in films]]\n[[Category:India\u2013Pakistan relations in popular culture]]\n[[Category:Military of Pakistan in films]]\n", "name_user": "Jerinkv", "label": "safe", "comment": "More information about Amrish Puri's role in the film.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vijeta_(1982_film)"}
{"title_page": "List of shopping streets and districts by city", "text_new": "{{short description|Wikimedia list article}}\n{{multiple issues|{{List dispute|date=November 2016}}\n{{refimprove|date=January 2015}}\n}}\n{{About|leading shopping streets|shopping malls|Lists of shopping malls}}\n\nThis page lists '''shopping streets and districts by city'''. Typically these are open-air street-side upscale shopping districts that are destination locations in cities. They may be located along a designated street, or clustered in mixed-use commercial area within the city. In the large cities, there may be multiple shopping streets or districts, often with distinct characteristics.\n\n{{TOC right}}\n\n==Africa==\n===Cameroon===\n* [[Yaounde]]: [[Avenue Kennedy]]\n* [[Douala]]: [[Avenue Ahmadou Ahidjo]], Boulevard de la libert\u00e9\n\n===Egypt===\n* [[Cairo]]: [[Khan el-Khalili]], [[Al-Husssein Area]]\n* [[Alexandria]]: [[Manshiya]], [[Berkleley]]\n* [[Sharm El-Sheikh]]: [[Naama Bay]], [[Shark's Bay]]\n\n===Ghana===\n* [[Accra]]: [[Oxford Street, Accra|Oxford Street]]\n\n===Morocco===\n* [[Casablanca]]: [[Place des shopping plaes]]\n\n===South Africa===\n* [[Johannesburg]]: [[Rosebank, Gauteng|Rosebank]], [[Sandton]]\n* [[Cape Town]]: [[Long Street (Cape Town)]]\n\n===Tunisia===\n* [[Tunis]]: [[Berges du Lac]]\n\n==Asia==\n\n===Armenia===\n*[[Yerevan]]: [[Northern Avenue (Yerevan)|Northern Avenue]]\n\n===Azerbaijan===\n[[File:Nizami street historical buildings.JPG|thumb|upright|[[Nizami Street]], [[Baku]], [[Azerbaijan]]]]\n*[[Baku]]: [[Neftchilar Avenue]], [[Nizami Street]]\n*[[Ganja, Azerbaijan|Ganja]]: [[Javad Khan Street]]\n\n===Bangladesh===\n*[[Dhaka]]: [[Gulshan Thana|Gulshan]]\n\n===Georgia===\n*[[Tbilisi]]: [[Rustaveli Avenue]]\n\n===Mainland China===\n<!--\n====Anhui====\n-->\n\n====Beijing====\n*[[Wangfujing]]<ref>{{cite news|title=...Wangfujing, one of Beijing's most famous shopping streets...|url=http://www.china.org.cn/china/2010-09/01/content_20841287.htm|accessdate=21 September 2010|newspaper=China.org.cn|date=1 September 2010}}</ref>\n*[[Xidan]]\n*[[Guomao, Beijing|Guomao]]\n*[[Zhongguancun]]\n*[[Sanlitun]]\n*[[Silk Street]]\n\n====Chongqing====\n*[[Ciqikou, Chongqing|Ciqikou]]\n*[[Guanyinqiao CBD|Guanyinqiao]]\n*[[Jiefangbei CBD|Jiefangbei]]\n*[[Nanping CBD|Nanping]]\n*[[Shapingba CBD|Shapingba]]\n\n====Fujian====\n*[[Xiamen]]: [[Zhongshan Road]], [[Xiahe Road]], [[Gulangyu Island]]\n<!--\n====Gansu====\n-->\n[[File:\u842c\u8c61\u57ce\u9580\u524d The Mixc - panoramio.jpg|thumb|227x227px|The MixC in [[Shenzhen]]]]\n\n====Guangdong====\n*[[Guangzhou]]: [[Shangxiajiu Pedestrian Street]]\n*[[Shenzhen]]: [[Shennan Road]], [[The MixC]]\n<!--\n====Guangxi====\n====Guangxi====\n====Guizhou====\n====Hainan====\n====Hebei====\n====Heilongjiang====\n====Henan====\n====Hubei====\n====Hunan====\n====Inner Mongolia====\n-->\n\n====Jiangsu====\n*[[Suzhou]]: [[Ligongdi]], [[Lake Jinji]], [[Shiquan Street]], [[Canglang]], [[Pingjiang Road]]\n<!--\n====Jilin====\n-->\n\n====Liaoning====\n[[File:\u9752\u6ce5\u6d3c\u6865.JPG|thumb|[[Qingniwaqiao]] in [[Dalian]], [[Liaoning Province]], [[China]]]]\n*[[Dalian]]: [[Qingniwaqiao]], [[Xi'an Road Commercial Zone|Xi'an Road]], Heping Square\n<!--\n====Ningxia====\n====Qinghai====\n-->\n\n====Shaanxi====\n*[[Xi'an]]: [[Eastern Street, Xian|Eastern Street]]\n\n====Shandong====\n*[[Qingdao]]: Taidong\n\n====Shanghai====\n[[File:Shanghai - Nanjing Road.jpeg|thumb|right|[[Nanjing Road (Shanghai)|Nanjing Road]], [[Shanghai]]]]\n*[[Nanjing Road East]], [[Nanjing Road West]]\n*[[Avenue Joffre]]\n*[[People's Square]]\n*[[Zikawei]]\n*[[Lujiazui]]\n*[[The Bund (Shanghai)|The Bund]]\n*[[Wujiaochang]]\n*[[Avenue Petain]]\n*[[Jing'an Temple]]\n*[[Dapu Bridge]]\n*[[Zhongshan Park]]\n*[[Hongqiao Subdistrict, Shanghai|Hongqiao]]\n*[[City God Temple]]\n*[[Xintiandi]]\n*[[Daning, Shanghai|Daning]]\n*[[Huamu]]\n*[[Tianzifang]]\n*[[Zhujiajiao]]\n*[[French Concession]]\n*[[Shanghai Railway Station]]\n*[[Qibao]]\n*[