ndependence]]. The book was republished in 1976 by [[Da Capo Press]]. In 1992 a second edition was published by Taiwan Publishing Co. The book is now legally available online (''see link below'').\n\n''Okinawa: The History of an Island People'' covers the legendary past to the [[Battle of Okinawa]] in 542 very read-able pages. Eleven years before he died, Kerr wrote that 13,000 copies had been sold. The book was out of print for a time, but Tuttle, the original publishers, reprinted it in 2000, adding a new introduction and an appendix by Okinawa history scholar Mitsugu Sakihara.<ref>{{cite web |title=Okinawa: History of an Island People |website=Tuttle Publishing |url=http://www.tuttlepublishing.com/book/?GCOI=48053100403940 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20130412003350/http://www.tuttlepublishing.com/book/?GCOI=48053100403940 |url-status=dead |archive-date=12 April 2013 |accessdate=8 Feb 2013 }}</ref>\n\nHe died at the age of 80 on August 27, 1992 in [[Honolulu, Hawaii]].<ref name=\"Register\" />\n\n==Selected works==\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |others=Afterword by Mitsugu Sakihara |date=2000 |title=Okinawa, the History of an Island People |place=Tokyo |publisher=Tuttle |isbn=9780804820875 |orig-year=1958}}\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1986 |title=The Taiwan confrontation crisis |place=Washington, D.C. |publisher=Formosan Association for Public Affairs |oclc=15681913}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1974 |title=Formosa: Licensed Revolution and the Home Rule Movement, 1895-1945 |place=Honolulu |publisher=University of Hawaii Press |isbn=9780824803230 |oclc=1174316}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1965 |title=Formosa Betrayed |place=Boston |publisher=Houghton Mifflin |ol=5948105M |oclc=242620|title-link=Formosa Betrayed (1965 book) }}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |last2=Higa |first2=Shuncho |date=1961 |title=Bibliography of the Ryukyus |place=[[Nishihara, Okinawa]] |publisher=[[University of the Ryukyus]] |oclc=8973627}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1959 |title=Science Information Services in Japan, a Brief Survey |place=Tokyo |oclc=22194372}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1958 |title=Okinawa: the History of an Island People |place=Tokyo |publisher=C. E. Tuttle Co. |oclc=468346635}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1953 |title=Ryukyu Kingdom and Province before 1945 |url=https://archive.org/details/bub_gb_Q5IrAAAAYAAJ |publisher=Pacific Science Board, National Academy of Sciences, National Research Council (US) |location=Washington |oclc=5455582}}<ref name=\"Register\" />\n*{{cite book |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |date=1952 |title=The Ry\u016bky\u016b Islands: A Preliminary Checklist of Reference Materials Arranged Alphabetically |others=Higa Shuncho and others |publisher=National Research Council (U.S.). Pacific Science Board. |oclc=79293918}}<ref>{{cite journal |last1=SHIMIZU |first1=Osamu |last2=KURODA |first2=Andrew Y. |title=Japan and the Ryukyu Islands |journal=The Quarterly Journal of the Library of Congress |date=1965 |volume=22 |issue=2 |pages=128\u2013137 |jstor=29781163 |quote=was issued in only about 50 mimeographed copies as an alphabetical listing by author of both monographs and serials, with a separate section for manuscript material.}}</ref>\n*{{Cite report |last1=Kerr |first1=George H. |last2=Stuart |first2=John Leighton |authorlink2=John Leighton Stuart |date={{date|1947-04-21|mdy}} |title=Memorandum on the Situation in Taiwan |publisher=American Embassy, Nanking, China |docket=Telegram No. 689 |accessdate={{date|2014-11-14|mdy}} |ref=harv}} reprinted in {{cite book |others=Compiled by [[Dean Acheson]] |publisher=U.S. Govt. Print. Off. |location=Washington |date=August 1949 |title=United States relations with China, with special reference to the period 1944-1949, based on the files of the Department of State |series=Far Eastern Series |issue=30 |pages=923\u2013938 |url=http://hdl.handle.net/2027/umn.31951d01115459w?urlappend=%3Bseq=969 |oclc=664471448}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n{{refbegin}}\n* A.P. Jenkins, 'G.H. Kerr's Okinawa: The History of an Island People and Beyond', The Ryukyuanist, No.52, Summer 2001, pp.&nbsp;3\u20138 (on which significant parts of this article are based but without due acknowledgement)\n{{refend}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.lib.u-ryukyu.ac.jp/biblio/bib32-3/bib32-3-5.html  University of the Ryukyus library]\n* [https://archive.today/20081019060351/http://www.archives.pref.okinawa.jp/collection/2007/04/hgeorge-hkerr.html George H. Kerr collection at Okinawa Prefectural Archives]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kerr, George H.}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1992 deaths]]\n[[Category:February 28 Incident]]\n[[Category:United States Navy reservists]]\n[[Category:United States naval attach\u00e9s]]\n[[Category:20th-century American writers]]\n[[Category:Hoover Institution people]]\n[[Category:University of Washington faculty]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Taiwan]]\n[[Category:American expatriates in Japan]]\n[[Category:Stanford University faculty]]\n[[Category:University of California, Berkeley faculty]]\n[[Category:American diplomats]]\n", "name_user": "Derim Hunt", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eAcademic career", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_H._Kerr"}
{"title_page": "Union Mall", "text_new": "{{Infobox shopping mall\n | name             = Union Mall\n | native_name      = {{lang|th|\u0e22\u0e39\u0e40\u0e19\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e19 \u0e21\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e25\u0e4c}}\n | image            = Union Mall Ladprao.jpg\n | caption          = \n | location         = [[Chatuchak (district)|Chatuchak]], [[Bangkok]]\n | coordinates      = {{coord|13.813587|100.561841|type:landmark_region:TH|display=inline,title}}\n | opening_date     = 2006\n | developer        = \n | manager          = \n | owner            = \n | number_of_stores = 1240\n | floors           = 8\n | floor_area       = {{convert|150,000|m2}}\n | parking          = 2000\n | website          = \n}}\n\n'''Union Mall''' is a shopping mall in the north of [[Bangkok]], at the [[Lat Phrao Intersection|Lat Phrao]] junction. The mall opened on February 2006. It has eight floors with a total of {{convert|150,000|m2}} of space. It houses some 1,240 booths and shops and entertainment services.<ref>[http://www.bangkok.com/shopping-mall/index.html#union-mall-bangkok Asia Web, Union Mall]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of shopping malls in Bangkok]]\n*[[List of shopping malls in Thailand]]\n*[[List of largest shopping malls in Thailand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bangkok Malls}}\n{{Shopping malls in Thailand}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Chatuchak District]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Thailand]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox shopping mall\n | name             = Union Mall\n | native_name      = {{lang|th|\u0e22\u0e39\u0e40\u0e19\u0e35\u0e48\u0e22\u0e19 \u0e21\u0e2d\u0e25\u0e25\u0e4c}}\n | image            = Union Mall Ladprao.jpg\n | caption          = \n | location         = [[Chatuchak (district)|Chatuchak]], [[Bangkok]]\n | coordinates      = {{coord|13.813587|100.561841|type:landmark_region:TH|display=inline,title}}\n | opening_date     = 2006\n | developer        = \n | manager          = \n | owner            = \n | number_of_stores = 1240\n | floors           = 8\n | floor_area       = {{convert|150,000|m2}}\n | parking          = 2000\n | website          = \n}}\n\n'''Union Mall''' is a shopping mall in the north of [[Bangkok]], at the [[Lat Phrao]] junction. The mall opened on February 2006. It has eight floors with a total of {{convert|150,000|m2}} of space. It houses some 1,240 booths and shops and entertainment services.<ref>[http://www.bangkok.com/shopping-mall/index.html#union-mall-bangkok Asia Web, Union Mall]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of shopping malls in Bangkok]]\n*[[List of shopping malls in Thailand]]\n*[[List of largest shopping malls in Thailand]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Bangkok Malls}}\n{{Shopping malls in Thailand}}\n\n[[Category:Shopping malls in Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Chatuchak District]]\n[[Category:Shopping malls established in 2006]]\n[[Category:2006 establishments in Thailand]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLat Phrao(link changed toLat Phrao Intersection) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Union_Mall"}
{"title_page": "Puri (food)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|Pur\u00e9e}}\n{{About|bread from the Bangladesh subcontinent|the extinct Indigenous people of Brazil|Pur\u00ed people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Puri\n| image            = Puri A.jpg\n| image_size       = 340px\n| caption          = Puris\n| country          = [[Indian Subcontinent]]\n| region           = Indian Subcontinent, [[Southeast Asia]]\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]], [[Nepali cuisine|Nepal]], [[Malaysian cuisine|Malaysia]], [[Burmese cuisine|Myanmar]], [[Singaporean cuisine|Singapore]]  \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[atta flour|Atta]]\n| variations       = [[Bhatoora]], [[Luchi]], [[Sevpuri]], [[Panipuri]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = true <!-- the category Puri on Commons is about the city -->\n}}\n\n'''Puri''' (also spelled '''Poori''') is a [[Deep fry|deep-fried]] bread made from [[leavening agent|unleavened]] [[whole-wheat flour]] that originated in the [[Indian subcontinent]]. It is eaten for [[breakfast]] or as a [[snack]] or [[light meal]]. It is usually served with a savory curry or ''bhaji'', as in [[puri bhaji]], but may also be eaten with sweet dishes.\n\nPuris are most commonly served at breakfast. It is also served at special or ceremonial functions as part of ceremonial rituals along with other [[vegetarian]] food offered in prayer as [[prasadam]].\n\n== Name ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2017}}\nThe name ''puri'' derives from the [[Sanskrit]] word \u092a\u0942\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e (p\u016brik\u0101), from \u092a\u0941\u0930 (pura) \"filled\". It has a similar name in many Asian languages including: [[Gujarati language|Gujarati:]] \u0aaa\u0ac2\u0ab0\u0ac0, {{lang-as|\u09aa\u09c1\u09f0\u09bf}} (''puri''), {{lang-bn|\u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09bf}} (''Pur\u012b''), {{lang-hi|\u092a\u0942\u0921\u093c\u0940}} (''p\u016b\u1e0d\u012b''), {{lang-mr|\u092a\u0942\u0930\u0940}} (''p\u016br\u012b''), {{lang-kn|\u0caa\u0cc2\u0cb0\u0cbf}}  (''p\u016bri''), {{lang-ml|\u0d2a\u0d42\u0d30\u0d3f}}, {{lang-my|\u1015\u1030\u101b\u102e}} (''p\u016br\u012b''), {{lang-ne|\u092a\u0942\u0930\u0940}} (''puri''), {{lang-or|\u0b2a\u0b41\u0b30\u0b3f}} (''puri''), {{lang-pa|\u0a2a\u0a41\u0a5c\u0a40}} (''p\u016b\u1e0d\u012b''), {{lang-ta|\u0baa\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bbf}} (''p\u016bri''), {{lang-te|\u0c2a\u0c42\u0c30\u0c3f}} (''p\u016bri''), [[Georgian language|Georgian]]: \u10de\u10e3\u10e0\u10d8 (p'uri), {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}}} (''puri'')\n\n== Ingredients ==\nPuris are prepared with wheat flour, either [[atta flour|atta]] ([[whole wheat flour]]), [[semolina|sooji]] (coarse wheat flour) or, most commonly, [[maida flour|maida]] (refined wheat flour). In some recipes, [[ajwain]] or [[cumin seed]] is added to the dough. The [[dough]] is either rolled out in a small circle or rolled out and cut out in small circles, then deep fried in [[ghee]] or vegetable oil.  While deep frying, puris puff up like a round ball because moisture in the dough changes into steam which expands in all directions. When they are golden-brown in color, they are removed and either served hot or saved for later use (as with the snack food [[pani puri]]). Rolled puris may be pricked with a fork before deep frying to make flat puris for [[chaat]] like [[bhel puri]]. A punctured puri does not puff when cooked because the steam escapes as it cooks.\n\n== Accompaniments ==\n<!-- Do NOT change the spelling of the image file! -->[[File:Poori wih accompaniments.jpg|thumb|Indian puri with accompaniments]]\nPuri can be eaten with many savory accompaniments, including [[korma]], [[chana masala]], [[dal]], potato-based curries (for example, ''saagu'', ''bhaji'', ''bhujia'', ''Aloo ki tarkari'', ''shaak'', and ''sambharo''), [[shrikhand]] and [[basundi]]. In some parts of India, puri is also served with a mixed vegetable dish that is prepared during [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]]. Puri is also eaten with sweet accompaniments, such as [[kheer]] (a dessert prepared with rice, milk and sugar) or [[halwa]] (in Hindi-speaking regions of India, the expression \"Halwa puri khana\", \"to eat puri with halwa\", signifies a celebration \u2013 of possibly modest means). Puri is often the bread of choice for festivals and special occasions.\n\nIn the South of India, puri is almost always made for tiffin, and on the east coast (Andhra, Tamil Nadu) it's rarely eaten with non-vegetarian dishes. Often, they will be served with pickles, chutneys, dal masalas, potato masala, or gourd curry (either ivy, ridge, or bottle varieties).\n\n== Types, variants ==\nA variant of puri is [[bhatoora]], which is three times the size of a puri and served with [[chana masala|chholey]] (spicy chick peas). It often constitutes a full meal. (See [[chole bhature]]). Bhatoora bread is with yeast and puri bread made from unleavened dough.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ramineni |first=Shubhra |title=Entice With Spice: Easy Indian Recipes for Busy People |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LpXTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT206}}</ref>\n\nIn the Indian state of [[Odisha]] a large size puri is made during [[Bali Yatra]] which is called ''thunka puri'' ({{Lang-or|\u0b20\u0b41\u0b19\u0b4d\u0b15\u0b3e \u0b2a\u0b41\u0b30\u0b3f}}).<ref>[http://cmccuttack.gov.in/overview_on_cuttack.html Overview of Cuttack]</ref><ref>[http://www.odiaa.com/2011/11/fanfare-spectacle-mark-the-opening-of-bali-yatra/ Fanfare & spectacle mark the opening of Bali Yatra] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403141410/http://www.odiaa.com/2011/11/fanfare-spectacle-mark-the-opening-of-bali-yatra/ |date=3 April 2015}}, 10 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://orissadiary.com/CurrentNews.asp?id=22539 Orissa CM Naveen Patnaik inaugurates historic Baliyatra festival in Cuttack], 22 November 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.odishanewstoday.com/entertainment/1279-bali-yatra-fever-grips-cuttack.html Bali Yatra Fever grips Cuttack], 12 November 2011 {{deadlink|date=September 2019}}</ref><ref>''Binita Jaiswal'', [http://m.timesofindia.com/PDATOI/articleshow/10684108.cms Fanfare & spectacle mark the opening of Bali Yatra], 10 November 2011</ref>\n\nAnother variant, largely popular in the Northern Indian state of Uttar Pradesh is ''bedvi''. It is a saltier and stiffer version of the regular puri, and is often stuffed with lentils.\n\nAnother variant of the puri popular in the eastern states of West Bengal and Odisha is the [[luchi]]. In Assam, it is pronounced as ''lusi''. Luchis in Bengal are served with typical side dishes like aloor dum (potato preparation), begun bhaja (fried brinjal) and others\n\nThe ''puris'' used for ''[[panipuri]]'' are smaller, and are usually made crisper by the addition of ''[[semolina|rava/sooji]]'' (semolina) to the dough.\n\n[[Sev puri]] is an Indian snack offered by street vendors who serve [[chaat]].\n\nStreet vendors in [[Mumbai]] serve [[Bhelpuri|bhel]] in a throw-away folded leaf with a flat puri to scoop it.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"145px\">\nFile:Poori.jpg|Puri is traditionally deep fried.\nFile:Dal Puri.JPG|Dal puri, a traditional Bengali version\nFile:Aloo Puri, typical morning snack, Varanasi.jpg|Aloo Puri, typical morning snack, Varanasi\nFile:Pani Puri - Perfect Street food.JPG|Mini-puris are part of [[panipuri]] snack. It's crunchier in texture.\nFile:Puri (food), fried dough food at Wikipedia's 16th Birthday celebration in Chittagong (01).jpg|Daal puri, Bangladesh\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Kulcha]]\n* [[List of Indian breads]]\n* [[List of Pakistani breads]]\n* [[Khachapuri]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== Heading text ==\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\nWhole recipe\n[https://www.kgrnews.com/resipe/chole-bhature-recipe-chana-bhatura/ Whole recipe]\n\n== External links ==\n{{cookbook|Puri}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{Doughnut}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Pakistani bread}}\n{{Pakistani dishes}}\n{{Malaysian cuisine}}\n{{Burmese cuisine}}\n{{Street food}}\n\n[[Category:Indian fast food]]\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sindhi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Muhajir cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pakistani fast food]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Unleavened breads]]\n[[Category:Tamil cuisine]]\n[[Category:Odia cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nepalese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Telangana cuisine]]\n[[Category:Andhra cuisine]]\n[[Category:Karnataka cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian breads]]\n[[Category:Gujarati cuisine]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Burmese cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|Pur\u00e9e}}\n{{About|bread from the Bangladesh subcontinent|the extinct Indigenous people of Brazil|Pur\u00ed people}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Puri\n| image            = Puri A.jpg\n| image_size       = 340px\n| caption          = Puris\n| country          = [[Indian Subcontinent]]\n| region           = Indian Subcontinent, [[Southeast Asia]]\n| national_cuisine = [[Indian cuisine|India]], [[Bangladeshi cuisine|Bangladesh]], [[Pakistani cuisine|Pakistan]], [[Nepali cuisine|Nepal]], [[Malaysian cuisine|Malaysia]], [[Burmese cuisine|Myanmar]], [[Singaporean cuisine|Singapore]]  \n| creator          = \n| course           = \n| served           = Hot\n| main_ingredient  = [[atta flour|Atta]]\n| variations       = [[Bhatoora]], [[Luchi]], [[Sevpuri]], [[Panipuri]]\n| calories         = \n| other            = \n| no_commons       = true <!-- the category Puri on Commons is about the city -->\n}}\n\n'''Puri''' (also spelled '''Poori''') is a [[Deep fry|deep-fried]] bread made from [[leavening agent|unleavened]] [[whole-wheat flour]] that originated in the [[Indian subcontinent]]. It is eaten for [[breakfast]] or as a [[snack]] or [[light meal]]. It is usually served with a savory curry or ''bhaji'', as in [[puri bhaji]], but may also be eaten with sweet dishes.\n\nPuris are most commonly served at breakfast. It is also served at special or ceremonial functions as part of ceremonial rituals along with other [[vegetarian]] food offered in prayer as [[prasadam]].\n\n== Name ==\n{{unreferenced section|date=May 2017}}\nThe name ''puri'' derives from the [[Sanskrit]] word \u092a\u0942\u0930\u093f\u0915\u093e (p\u016brik\u0101), from \u092a\u0941\u0930 (pura) \"filled\". It has a similar name in many Asian languages including: [[Gujarati language|Gujarati:]] \u0aaa\u0ac2\u0ab0\u0ac0, {{lang-as|\u09aa\u09c1\u09f0\u09bf}} (''puri''), {{lang-bn|\u09aa\u09c1\u09b0\u09bf}} (''Pur\u012b''), {{lang-hi|\u092a\u0942\u0921\u093c\u0940}} (''p\u016b\u1e0d\u012b''), {{lang-mr|\u092a\u0942\u0930\u0940}} (''p\u016br\u012b''), {{lang-kn|\u0caa\u0cc2\u0cb0\u0cbf}}  (''p\u016bri''), {{lang-ml|\u0d2a\u0d42\u0d30\u0d3f}}, {{lang-my|\u1015\u1030\u101b\u102e}} (''p\u016br\u012b''), {{lang-ne|\u092a\u0942\u0930\u0940}} (''puri''), {{lang-or|\u0b2a\u0b41\u0b30\u0b3f}} (''puri''), {{lang-pa|\u0a2a\u0a41\u0a5c\u0a40}} (''p\u016b\u1e0d\u012b''), {{lang-ta|\u0baa\u0bc2\u0bb0\u0bbf}} (''p\u016bri''), {{lang-te|\u0c2a\u0c42\u0c30\u0c3f}} (''p\u016bri''), [[Georgian language|Georgian]]: \u10de\u10e3\u10e0\u10d8 (p'uri), {{lang-ur|{{Nastaliq|\u067e\u0648\u0631\u06cc}}}} (''puri'')\n\n== Ingredients ==\nPuris are prepared with wheat flour, either [[atta flour|atta]] ([[whole wheat flour]]), [[semolina|sooji]] (coarse wheat flour) or, most commonly, [[maida flour|maida]] (refined wheat flour). In some recipes, [[ajwain]] or [[cumin seed]] is added to the dough. The [[dough]] is either rolled out in a small circle or rolled out and cut out in small circles, then deep fried in [[ghee]] or vegetable oil.  While deep frying, puris puff up like a round ball because moisture in the dough changes into steam which expands in all directions. When they are golden-brown in color, they are removed and either served hot or saved for later use (as with the snack food [[pani puri]]). Rolled puris may be pricked with a fork before deep frying to make flat puris for [[chaat]] like [[bhel puri]]. A punctured puri does not puff when cooked because the steam escapes as it cooks.\n\n== Accompaniments ==\n<!-- Do NOT change the spelling of the image file! -->[[File:Poori wih accompaniments.jpg|thumb|Indian puri with accompaniments]]\nPuri can be eaten with many savory accompaniments, including [[korma]], [[chana masala]], [[dal]], potato-based curries (for example, ''saagu'', ''bhaji'', ''bhujia'', ''Aloo ki tarkari'', ''shaak'', and ''sambharo''), [[shrikhand]] and [[basundi]]. In some parts of India, puri is also served with a mixed vegetable dish that is prepared during [[Puja (Hinduism)|Puja]]. Puri is also eaten with sweet accompaniments, such as [[kheer]] (a dessert prepared with rice, milk and sugar) or [[halwa]] (in Hindi-speaking regions of India, the expression \"Halwa puri khana\", \"to eat puri with halwa\", signifies a celebration \u2013 of possibly modest means). Puri is often the bread of choice for festivals and special occasions.\n\nIn the South of India, puri is almost always made for tiffin, and on the east coast (Andhra, Tamil Nadu) it's rarely eaten with non-vegetarian dishes. Often, they will be served with pickles, chutneys, dal masalas, potato masala, or gourd curry (either ivy, ridge, or bottle varieties).\n\n== Types, variants ==\nA variant of puri is [[bhatoora]], which is three times the size of a puri and served with [[chana masala|chholey]] (spicy chick peas). It often constitutes a full meal. (See [[chole bhature]]). Bhatoora bread is with yeast and puri bread made from unleavened dough.<ref>{{cite book |last=Ramineni |first=Shubhra |title=Entice With Spice: Easy Indian Recipes for Busy People |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=LpXTAgAAQBAJ&pg=PT206}}</ref>\n\nIn the Indian state of [[Odisha]] a large size puri is made during [[Bali Yatra]] which is called ''thunka puri'' ({{Lang-or|\u0b20\u0b41\u0b19\u0b4d\u0b15\u0b3e \u0b2a\u0b41\u0b30\u0b3f}}).<ref>[http://cmccuttack.gov.in/overview_on_cuttack.html Overview of Cuttack]</ref><ref>[http://www.odiaa.com/2011/11/fanfare-spectacle-mark-the-opening-of-bali-yatra/ Fanfare & spectacle mark the opening of Bali Yatra] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403141410/http://www.odiaa.com/2011/11/fanfare-spectacle-mark-the-opening-of-bali-yatra/ |date=3 April 2015}}, 10 November 2011</ref><ref>[http://orissadiary.com/CurrentNews.asp?id=22539 Orissa CM Naveen Patnaik inaugurates historic Baliyatra festival in Cuttack], 22 November 2010</ref><ref>[http://www.odishanewstoday.com/entertainment/1279-bali-yatra-fever-grips-cuttack.html Bali Yatra Fever grips Cuttack], 12 November 2011 {{deadlink|date=September 2019}}</ref><ref>''Binita Jaiswal'', [http://m.timesofindia.com/PDATOI/articleshow/10684108.cms Fanfare & spectacle mark the opening of Bali Yatra], 10 November 2011</ref>\n\nAnother variant, largely popular in the Northern Indian state of Uttar Pradesh is ''bedvi''. It is a saltier and stiffer version of the regular puri, and is often stuffed with lentils.\n\nAnother variant of the puri popular in the eastern states of West Bengal and Odisha is the [[luchi]]. In Assam, it is pronounced as ''lusi''. Luchis in Bengal are served with typical side dishes like aloor dum (potato preparation), begun bhaja (fried brinjal) and others\n\nThe ''puris'' used for ''[[panipuri]]'' are smaller, and are usually made crisper by the addition of ''[[semolina|rava/sooji]]'' (semolina) to the dough.\n\n[[Sev puri]] is an Indian snack offered by street vendors who serve [[chaat]].\n\nStreet vendors in [[Mumbai]] serve [[Bhelpuri|bhel]] in a throw-away folded leaf with a flat puri to scoop it.\n\n<gallery class=\"center\" caption=\"\" widths=\"180px\" heights=\"145px\">\nFile:Poori.jpg|Puri is traditionally deep fried.\nFile:Dal Puri.JPG|Dal puri, a traditional Bengali version\nFile:Aloo Puri, typical morning snack, Varanasi.jpg|Aloo Puri, typical morning snack, Varanasi\nFile:Pani Puri - Perfect Street food.JPG|Mini-puris are part of [[panipuri]] snack. It's crunchier in texture.\nFile:Puri (food), fried dough food at Wikipedia's 16th Birthday celebration in Chittagong (01).jpg|Daal puri, Bangladesh\n</gallery>\n\n== See also ==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[Kulcha]]\n* [[List of Indian breads]]\n* [[List of Pakistani breads]]\n* [[Khachapuri]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{cookbook|Puri}}\n{{Commons category}}\n\n{{Flatbreads}}\n{{Doughnut}}\n{{Indian bread}}\n{{Indian Dishes}}\n{{Pakistani bread}}\n{{Pakistani dishes}}\n{{Malaysian cuisine}}\n{{Burmese cuisine}}\n{{Street food}}\n\n[[Category:Indian fast food]]\n[[Category:Indian breads]]\n[[Category:Punjabi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sindhi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Muhajir cuisine]]\n[[Category:Pakistani fast food]]\n[[Category:Pakistani breads]]\n[[Category:Uttar Pradeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Flatbreads]]\n[[Category:Unleavened breads]]\n[[Category:Tamil cuisine]]\n[[Category:Odia cuisine]]\n[[Category:Bengali cuisine]]\n[[Category:Nepalese cuisine]]\n[[Category:Sri Lankan cuisine]]\n[[Category:Telangana cuisine]]\n[[Category:Andhra cuisine]]\n[[Category:Karnataka cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian cuisine]]\n[[Category:Malaysian breads]]\n[[Category:Gujarati cuisine]]\n[[Category:Deep fried foods]]\n[[Category:Bangladeshi cuisine]]\n[[Category:Burmese cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "Vijay kumar pg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eReferences)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Puri_(food)"}
