}\n[[Image:Bangkok Baiyoke Tower.jpg|right|180px|thumb|Baiyoke Tower 2 at [[Pratu Nam]] (second tallest building in Bangkok)]]\nThis is a partial list of neighbourhoods in [[Bangkok]].\n\n==[[Bang Kapi]]==\n*[[Bang Kapi]]\n*[[Chok Chai 4]]\n*[[Happy Land (Bangkok)|Happy Land]]\n*[[Hua Mak]]\n*[[Khlong Chan]]\n*[[Lam Sali]]\n*[[Lat Phrao]]\n*[[Ramkhamhaeng University|Ramkhamhaeng]]\n\n==[[Bang Sue]]==\n*[[Bang Pho]]\n*[[Bang Son]]\n*[[Bang Sue]]\n*[[Pracha Chuen]]\n*[[Tao Pun]]\n*[[Wong Sawang]]\n\n==[[Chatuchak (district)|Chatuchak]]==\n[[Image:Bangkok-sukhumvit-road-traffic-200503.jpg|right|180px|thumb|Traffic jam at Siam Square]]\n*[[Ari BTS station|Ari]]\n*[[Chatuchak Park]]\n*[[Bang Sue Junction|Chumtang Bang Sue]]\n*[[Kamphaeng Phet Road|Kamphaeng Phet]]\n*[[Lat Phrao Road|Lat Phrao]]\n*[[Mo Chit skytrain station|Mo Chit]]\n*[[Mo Chit 2]]\n*[[Phahon Yothin]]\n*[[Pradiphat]]\n*[[Ratchayothin]]\n*[[Saphan Khwai]]\n*[[Wat Samian Nari]]\n\n==[[Don Mueang]]==\n*[[Bang Khen]]\n*[[Don Mueang]]\n*[[Kaset Sat Station|Kaset]]\n*[[Lak Si]]\n*[[Ngam Wong Wan]]\n*[[Saphan Mai]]\n*[[Sena Nikhom]]\n*[[Thung Song Hong]]\n\n==[[Dusit District|Dusit]]==\n*[[Bang Krabue, Bangkok|Bang Krabue]]\n*[[Dusit Palace]]\n*[[Royal Plaza (Thailand)|Lan Phra Borommarup Song Ma]]\n*[[Kiak Kai]]\n*[[Si Yaek Maha Nak Subdistrict|Maha Nak]]\n*[[Ratchawat]]\n*[[Samsen]]\n*[[Sanam Suea Pa]]\n*[[Si Yan, Bangkok|Si Yan]]\n*[[Soi Suan Oi]]\n*[[Suan Amphon]]\n*[[Suan Chitlada]]\n\n==[[Pathum Wan]] (well known as ''[[Ratchaprasong]]'' [[List of leading shopping streets and districts by city|shopping street area]])==\n[[Image:New Year Ratchaprasong.jpg|right|220px|thumb|Lights in front of Amarin Plaza at Ratchaprasong]]\n*[[Ban Krua]]\n*[[Banthat Thong]]\n*[[Bon Kai]]\n*[[Charoen Phon]]\n*[[Chit Lom Station|Chit Lom]]\n*[[Chulalongkorn University|Chula]]\n*[[Hua Lamphong]]\n*[[Lang Suan (street)|Lang Suan]]\n*[[Suphachalasai Stadium|Suphachalasai (National Stadium)]]\n*[[Phloen Chit]]\n*[[Rama I Road|Phra Ram 1]]\n*[[Ratchadamri]]\n*[[Ratchaprasong]]\n*[[Sam Yan]]\n*[[Saphan Lueang]]\n*[[Siam Square]] ([[Shinjuku]] of Thailand)\n*[[Lumphini Park|Suan Lum]]\n*[[Witthayu Road|Witthayu]]\n\n==[[Phetchaburi Road|Phetchaburi]]==\n[[Image:Wat Phra Kaew outside view.jpg|200px|thumb|right|The Wat Phra Kaew temple at Sanam Luang]]\n*[[Indra, Bangkok|Indra]]\n*[[Khlong Tan]]\n*[[Makkasan]]\n*[[Pantip Plaza]]\n*[[Phet Rama]]\n*[[Pratu Nam]]\n*[[Ratchaprarop]]\n*[[Yommarat]]\n*[[Uruphong]]\n\n==[[Phra Nakhon]] (well known as ''[[Rattanakosin Island]]'')==\n[[Image:Kaoh San Road.jpg|right|200px|thumb|Khaosan Road at night]]\n[[file:Bangkok\u2019s Chinatown.jpg|200px|thumb|Under Saphan Phut at day]]\n*[[Ban Mo, Bangkok|Ban Mo]]\n*[[Bang Lamphu]]\n*[[Khaosan Road]]\n*[[Khlong Lot]]\n*[[Khok Wua]]\n*[[Pak Khlong Talat]]\n*[[Pratu Phi]]\n*[[Ratchadamnoen]]\n*[[Saphan Phut]] (Memorial Bridge)\n*[[Sam Phraeng]]\n*[[Sanam Luang]]\n*[[Sao Chingcha]]\n*[[Si Kak Phraya Si|Si Kak]]\n*[[Tha Phra Chan]]\n*[[Tha Tian Market|Tha Tian]]\n*[[Thewet]]\n\n==[[Pom Prap Sattru Phai]]==\n*[[Ban Bat]]\n*[[Bobae Market|Bobae]]\n*[[Maen Si]]\n*[[Talat Nang Loeng|Nang Loeng]]\n*[[Suan Mali]]\n*[[Suea Pa Intersection|Suea Pa]]\n*[[July 22nd Circle|Wong Wian Yi Sip Song Karakada Khom]]\n*[[Worachak Road|Worachak]]\n*[[Yotse]]\n\n==[[Ratchadaphisek]] or [[Ratchada]]==\n[[Image:Bangkok skytrain sunset.jpg|right|thumb|180px|Narathiwat Ratcha Nakharin]]\n*[[Chandrakasem Rajabhat University|Chan Kasem]]\n*[[Din Daeng]]\n*[[Huai Khwang]]\n*[[Meng Jai]]\n*[[Phra Ram 9]]\n*[[Pracha Songkhro]]\n*[[Sutthisan]]\n*[[Royal City Avenue|RCA]]\n*[[Thailand Cultural Centre]]\n*[[Town in Town]]\n\n==[[Sathon]]==\n[[Image:Bangkok Skytrain Saladaeng.jpg|thumb|right|200px|BTS Sala Daeng Station at Si Lom]]\n*[[Chong Nonsi]]\n*[[Krung Thon Buri]]\n*[[Lumphini Subdistrict|Lumphini]]\n*[[Naradhiwas Rajanagarindra Road|Naradhiwas Rajanagarindra]]\n*[[Phra Ram 3]]\n*[[Taksin Bridge|Saphan Taksin]]\n*[[Sathu Pradit]]\n*[[Surasak]]\n*[[Thanon Chan]]\n*[[Thanon Tok]]\n*[[Yan Nawa]]\n\n==[[Si Lom]]==\n[[Image:Hualamphong St001.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Inside Hua Lamphong (main railway station in Bangkok)]]\n*[[Bang Rak]]\n*[[Patpong]]\n*[[Sala Daeng]]\n*[[Silom]]\n*[[Si Phraya Road|Si Phraya]]\n*[[Soi Lalai Sap]]\n*[[Surawong]]\n*[[Thaniya]]\n\n==[[Srinagarindra Road|Sri Nakarin]]<ref>[http://www99.bangkokpost.com/news/crimes/318684/bar-guard-nabbed-for-killing-customer Bouncer charged in bar killing] {{webarchive|url=https://archive.is/20130118023344/http://www99.bangkokpost.com/news/crimes/318684/bar-guard-nabbed-for-killing-customer |date=2013-01-18 }}</ref>==\n*[[Bang Na]]\n*[[Soi Bearing|Bearing]]\n*[[BITEC|BITEC (Bangkok International Trade & Exhibition Centre)]]\n*[[Krungthep Kritha]]\n*[[Soi Lasalle|Lasalle]]\n*[[Nong Bon]]\n*[[Phatthanakan]]\n*[[Suan Luang]]\n*[[Wat Si Iam]]\n\n==[[Sukhumvit Road|Sukhumvit]]==\n[[Image:Wat Arun from Chao Phraya River.jpg|right|220px|thumb|Wat Arun]]\n*[[Asok Montri Road|Asok]]\n*[[Ekkamai]]\n*[[Khlong Toei]]\n*[[Kluai Nam Thai]]\n*[[Nana Intersection|Nana]]\n*[[On Nut]]\n*[[Phra Khanong]]\n*[[Rama IV Road|Phra Ram 4]]\n*[[Phrom Phong]]\n*[[Queen Sirikit National Convention Center|Queen Sirikit Center]]\n*[[Thong Lo]]\n*[[Udom Suk]]\n\n==[[Thon Buri]]==\n[[Image:Thonburi railway station.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Thonburi railway station at Siriraj]]\n[[image:Thanon Pran Nok 2018.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Phran Nok and Faichai]]\n[[image:Thanon Charan Sanit awong 2019-2-23.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Charan Sanit Wong near Faichai]]\n*[[Ban Khaek]]\n*[[Ban Khamin]]\n*[[Ban Noen, Bangkok|Ban Noen]]\n*[[Bang Bon]]\n*[[Bang Khae]]\n* [[Bang Khun Non]]\n*[[Bang Khun Thian]]\n*[[Khlong Bang Mot|Bang Mot]]\n*[[Bang Pakaeo]]\n*[[Bang Pakok]]\n*[[Bang Wa]]\n*[[Bang Kradi]]\n*[[Bukkhalo]]\n*[[Charan Sanit Wong]]\n*[[Charoen Nakhon]]\n*[[Charoen Rat Road|Charoen Rat]]\n*[[Dao Khanong Subdistrict|Dao Khanong]]\n*[[Faichai]]\n*[[Hua Krabue]]\n*[[Khlong San]]\n*[[Kudi Chin]]\n*[[Lak Song]]\n*[[Nong Khaem District|Nong Khaem]]\n*[[Pho Sam Ton]]\n*[[Phran Nok]]\n*[[Thailand Route 35|Phra Ram 2]]\n*[[Phra Pin-klao Bridge|Pinklao]]\n*[[Phuttha Bucha]]\n*[[Phutthamonthon]]\n*[[Rat Burana]]\n*[[Ratchaphruek]]\n*[[Samre, Bangkok|Samre]]\n*[[Sanam Luang 2]]\n*[[Siri Rat Subdistrict|Siri Rat]]\n*[[Talat Phlu]]\n*[[Taling Chan]]\n*[[Tha Din Daeng, Bangkok|Tha Din Daeng]]\n*[[Tha Phra]]\n*[[Thawi Watthana]]\n*[[Thung Khru]]\n*[[Wat Arun]]\n*[[Wang Lang Market|Wang Lang]]\n*[[Wong Wian Lek]]\n*[[Wong Wian Yai]]\n\n==[[Victory Monument (Bangkok)|Victory Monument]]==\n[[Image:Victory Monument-Bangkok.jpg|thumb|right|180px|Victory Monument in Bangkok]]\n*[[Phaya Thai Road|Phaya Thai]]\n*[[Ramathibodi Hospital|Ramathibodi]]\n*[[Ratchathewi]]\n*[[Ratchawithi Road|Ratchawithi]]\n*[[Sam Liam Din Daeng]]\n*[[Sanam Pao]]\n*[[Tuek Chai]]\n*[[Victory Monument (Bangkok)|Victory Monument]]\n\n==[[Wang Burapha]]==\n*[[Khlong Thom, Bangkok|Khlong Thom]]\n*[[Phahurat]] ([[Little India (location)|Little India]] of Bangkok)\n*[[Sam Yot]]\n*[[Saphan Lek]]\n*[[Wang Burapha]]\n*[[Thieves' Market|Woeng Nakhon Kasem]] (Thieves' Market)\n\n==[[Yaowarat]] ([[Bangkok's Chinatown|Chinatown of Bangkok]])==\n*[[Phlapphla Chai]]\n*[[Ratchawong Road|Ratchawong]]\n*[[Sampheng]]\n*[[Song Wat Road|Song Wat]]\n*[[Mo Mi|Sam Yaek]]\n*[[Saphan Han]]\n*[[Sieng Kong]]\n*[[Talat Noi]]\n*[[Yaowarat]]\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bangkok]]\n*[[MRT (Bangkok)|Bangkok MRT]]\n*[[BTS Skytrain|Bangkok Mass Transit System (BTS)]]\n*[[List of shopping malls in Thailand]]\n*[[Downtown]]\n*[[Central business district]]\n*[[List of leading shopping streets and districts by city]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Geography of Bangkok]]\n[[Category:Thailand geography-related lists|Bangkok districts]]\n[[Category:Bangkok-related lists|Districts]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toLat Phrao(link changed toLat Phrao District) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/List_of_neighbourhoods_in_Bangkok"}
{"title_page": "Joginder Sharma", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Joginder Sharma\n|               image = \n|             country = India\n|            fullname = Joginder Nath Sharma\n|            nickname = \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|10|23|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Rohtak]], [[Haryana]], India\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|             heightm = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right arm [[fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n|                role = [[All-rounder]]\n|       international = true\n|        odidebutdate = 23 December\n|        odidebutyear = 2004\n|     odidebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|              odicap = 155\n|         lastodidate = 20 January\n|         lastodiyear = 2007\n|      lastodiagainst = Sri Lanka\n|            odishirt = 23\n|       T20Idebutdate = 18 September\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2007\n|    T20Idebutagainst = England\n|             T20Icap = 6\n|        lastT20Idate = 24 September\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2007\n|     lastT20Iagainst = Pakistan\n|           T20Ishirt = 23\n|               club1 = [[Haryana cricket team|Haryana]]\n|               year1 = {{nowrap|2002/03\u20132016/17}}\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = [[Chennai Super Kings]]\n|               year2 = 2008\u20132012\n|         clubnumber2 = \n|               club3 = \n|               year3 = \n|         clubnumber3 = \n|               club4 = \n|               year4 = \n|         clubnumber4 = \n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches1 = 4\n|               runs1 = 35\n|            bat avg1 = 35.00\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 29[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries1 = 150\n|            wickets1 = 1\n|           bowl avg1 = 115.00\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 1/28\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 3/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n|            matches2 = 4\n|               runs2 = \u2013\n|            bat avg2 = \u2013\n|           100s/50s2 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score2 = \u2013\n|         deliveries2 = 87\n|            wickets2 = 4\n|           bowl avg2 = 34.50\n|            fivefor2 = 0\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 2/20\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 2/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 44\n|               runs3 = 2,043\n|            bat avg3 = 30.49\n|           100s/50s3 = 4/9\n|          top score3 = 139\n|         deliveries3 = 8,972\n|            wickets3 = 200\n|           bowl avg3 = 20.05\n|            fivefor3 = 14\n|             tenfor3 = 5\n|       best bowling3 = 8/24\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 4/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 45\n|               runs4 = 522\n|            bat avg4 = 18.64\n|           100s/50s4 = 0/0\n|          top score4 = 44\n|         deliveries4 = 2,018\n|            wickets4 = 63\n|           bowl avg4 = 25.41\n|            fivefor4 = 0\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 4/13\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 9/\u2013\n|                date = 20 September\n|                year = 2008\n|              source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44939/44939.html CricketArchive\n}}\n\n'''Joginder Shubhanshu Sharma''' {{audio|Joginder_Sharma.ogg|pronunciation}} (born 23 October 1983), better known as Joginder Sharma, is an Indian professional [[cricket]]er and a member of [[Civil Services of India#Construction|Haryana Police Service]] cadre who currently serves as [[Deputy superintendent of police]].{{what|date=August 2019}} He has made sporadic appearances for the [[Indian cricket team]].\n\n==Style of play==\nA bowling [[all rounder]], he played as a right-handed batsman and a right-arm medium-fast bowler and captained his state, [[Haryana cricket team|Haryana]].\n\n==First class==\nSharma made his first-class debut for Haryana against [[Madhya Pradesh cricket team|Madhya Pradesh]] in the 2002/03 [[Ranji Trophy]], hitting 81 before taking 11/84 to lead Haryana to a 103 run victory.<ref>{{cite web| title = Haryana vs Madhya Pradesh at Rohtak 9\u201312 November 2002| url= http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/PLATE/ROUND1/HRYNA_MP_RJI_09-12NOV2002.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> He had made his debut in the limited over domestic arena the season before.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|first =Siddhartha |last= Vaidyanathan| title = Joginder Sharma| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/current/player/29976.html |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]| accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Sharma finished his debut season with 24 wickets at 17.41 and 280 runs at 46.66<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> He followed this with 148 runs at 68.51 and 23 wickets at 23.39 in 2003/04 Ranji season.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> He was selected for the [[North Zone cricket team|North Zone]] team for the [[Duleep Trophy]], and took 6/59 in a match against [[West Zone cricket team|West Zone]] during the victorious campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title = Chopra guides North Zone home| url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/137102.html | publisher = [[Cricinfo]] | date = 2004-02-25 |accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==National attention==\n\nSharma gained national attention in a match for India A against the national team at [[Bangalore]], when he dismissed [[Rahul Dravid]], [[V. V. S. Laxman]] and [[Yuvraj Singh]].<ref name =\"profile\"/><ref>{{cite news|first = Dileep | last = Premachandran| title = India A take charge despite Ganguly's effort| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/143664.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]] |date = 29 September 2004 | accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> He also played for the Rest of India side, which defeated [[Mumbai cricket team|Mumbai]] in the [[Irani Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Rest of India crush Mumbai| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/143598.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]] |date = 25 September 2004 | accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref>\n\nHaving scored two successive centuries, and securing a 14/116 in the 2004/05 [[Ranji Trophy]] against [[Vidarbha cricket team|Vidarbha]],<ref>{{cite web| title = Vidarbha vs Haryana at Nagpur 13\u201316 December 2004| url= http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/PLATE/ROUND4/VIDAR_HRYNA_RJI_13-16DEC2004.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Sharma won his place in the Indian side for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour. He had limited batting opportunities, scoring 34 in two brief knocks at the end of the innings without being dismissed, but his bowling was ineffective, taking 1/99, and was dropped after playing in that ODI series.<ref name =\"statsguruodi\"/> He ended the Ranji Trophy with 36 wickets, the second highest at 15.47 and 472 runs at 52.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/CUM-STATS//IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/CUM-STATS//IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> In 2005/06, he topped the Duleep Trophy bowling averages.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Best averages | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/IND_LOCAL/DULEEP/STATS/IND_LOCAL_DULEEP_AVS_BOWL_BEST_AVS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic season==\n\nSharma performed strongly in the 2006/07 Indian domestic season to bring himself into contention for national selection. His batting for [[North Zone cricket team|North Zone]] in the [[Duleep Trophy]] yielded 421 runs in three matches, and he was subsequently the leading wicket-taker in the Ranji Trophy, taking 39 wickets in seven matches, as well as two ten-wicket hauls and a [[hat trick]].<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cite news|first = Siddhartha |last = Vaidyanathan| title = Joginder gets a second chance|url= http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/276253.html|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]| date = 12 January 2007| accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Despite being unable to prevent Haryana from being relegated to the Plate division, he was recalled in January 2007 to the team at the expense of [[Irfan Pathan]] for the ODI series against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]].<ref name = \"cricinfo\"/> He was selected for the second ODI in [[Cuttack]], but after scoring 1 and failing to take a wicket,<ref name=\"statsguruodi\">{{cite web|title = Statsguru \u2013 Joginder Sharma \u2013 ODIs \u2013 Innings by innings list| url = http://statserver.cricket.org/guru?sdb=player;playerid=45592;class=odiplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=2004-12-23;start=2004-12-23;enddefault=2007-01-24;end=2007-01-24;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;viewtype=aro_list;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;csearch=;submit=1;.cgifields=viewtype |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Pathan was immediately recalled and Sharma dropped. Sharma was not named in the Indian squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]]. \n\n==International Career==\n\nSharma found a place for himself in the [[2007 World Twenty20]]  in South Africa. He bowled the final over of the semi final against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]], with [[Michael Hussey]] facing and Australia needing 22 runs to win, taking two wickets as India won by 15 runs.\n\nHe also bowled the final over in the final against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]] with thirteen runs required and only one wicket in hand. His first ball went for a [[wide (cricket)|wide]] and the next was borderline but not called by the umpire. The third was a [[full toss]] which was pulled straight back over his head for six by [[Misbah-ul-Haq]]. Then he [https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/commentary/287879/india-vs-pakistan-final-icc-world-twenty20-2007-08 bowled a beautiful] delivery out side off stump which Misbah attempted to [[Marillier shot|scoop]] the ball over the fine leg fielder from the fourth ball but mistimed it and was caught by [[Sreesanth]], giving India the win. The [[Government of Haryana|Haryana government]] announced a cash reward of Rs 21 lakh for Joginder Sharma in recognition of his contribution to the Indian victory.<ref>{{cite web |title = Haryana CM announces Rs.21 lakh cash reward for Joginder Sharma |url = http://www.punjabnewsline.com/content/view/5828/94/ |publisher = Punjab Newsline Network |accessdate = 2007-09-26 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130131232544/http://www.punjabnewsline.com/content/view/5828/94/ |archivedate = 31 January 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> His winning moment had earned him a job with Haryana Police. Now 13 years later, he enjoys life as a Deputy superintendent Of Police.\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{India Squad 2007 Cricket World Twenty20}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Joginder}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian cricketers]]\n[[Category:India One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:India Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Haryana cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Rohtak]]\n[[Category:Chennai Super Kings cricketers]]\n[[Category:North Zone cricketers]]\n[[Category:India Blue cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Haryana]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Infobox cricketer\n|                name = Joginder Sharma\n|               image = \n|             country = India\n|            fullname = Joginder Nath Sharma\n|            nickname = \n|          birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1983|10|23|df=yes}}\n|         birth_place = [[Rohtak]], [[Haryana]], India\n|            heightft = \n|          heightinch = \n|             heightm = \n|             batting = Right-handed\n|             bowling = Right arm [[fast bowling|fast-medium]]\n|                role = [[All-rounder]]\n|       international = true\n|        odidebutdate = 23 December\n|        odidebutyear = 2004\n|     odidebutagainst = Bangladesh\n|              odicap = 155\n|         lastodidate = 20 January\n|         lastodiyear = 2007\n|      lastodiagainst = Sri Lanka\n|            odishirt = 23\n|       T20Idebutdate = 18 September\n|       T20Idebutyear = 2007\n|    T20Idebutagainst = England\n|             T20Icap = 6\n|        lastT20Idate = 24 September\n|        lastT20Iyear = 2007\n|     lastT20Iagainst = Pakistan\n|           T20Ishirt = 23\n|               club1 = [[Haryana cricket team|Haryana]]\n|               year1 = {{nowrap|2002/03\u20132016/17}}\n|         clubnumber1 = \n|               club2 = [[Chennai Super Kings]]\n|               year2 = 2008\u20132012\n|         clubnumber2 = \n|               club3 = \n|               year3 = \n|         clubnumber3 = \n|               club4 = \n|               year4 = \n|         clubnumber4 = \n|             columns = 4\n|             column1 = [[One Day International|ODI]]\n|            matches1 = 4\n|               runs1 = 35\n|            bat avg1 = 35.00\n|           100s/50s1 = 0/0\n|          top score1 = 29[[not out|*]]\n|         deliveries1 = 150\n|            wickets1 = 1\n|           bowl avg1 = 115.00\n|            fivefor1 = 0\n|             tenfor1 = 0\n|       best bowling1 = 1/28\n|  catches/stumpings1 = 3/\u2013\n|             column2 = [[Twenty20 International|T20I]]\n|            matches2 = 4\n|               runs2 = \u2013\n|            bat avg2 = \u2013\n|           100s/50s2 = \u2013/\u2013\n|          top score2 = \u2013\n|         deliveries2 = 87\n|            wickets2 = 4\n|           bowl avg2 = 34.50\n|            fivefor2 = 0\n|             tenfor2 = 0\n|       best bowling2 = 2/20\n|  catches/stumpings2 = 2/\u2013\n|             column3 = [[First-class cricket|FC]]\n|            matches3 = 44\n|               runs3 = 2,043\n|            bat avg3 = 30.49\n|           100s/50s3 = 4/9\n|          top score3 = 139\n|         deliveries3 = 8,972\n|            wickets3 = 200\n|           bowl avg3 = 20.05\n|            fivefor3 = 14\n|             tenfor3 = 5\n|       best bowling3 = 8/24\n|  catches/stumpings3 = 4/\u2013\n|             column4 = [[List A cricket|LA]]\n|            matches4 = 45\n|               runs4 = 522\n|            bat avg4 = 18.64\n|           100s/50s4 = 0/0\n|          top score4 = 44\n|         deliveries4 = 2,018\n|            wickets4 = 63\n|           bowl avg4 = 25.41\n|            fivefor4 = 0\n|             tenfor4 = 0\n|       best bowling4 = 4/13\n|  catches/stumpings4 = 9/\u2013\n|                date = 20 September\n|                year = 2008\n|              source = https://cricketarchive.com/Archive/Players/44/44939/44939.html CricketArchive\n}}\n\n'''Joginder Sharma''' {{audio|Joginder_Sharma.ogg|pronunciation}} (born 23 October 1983) is an Indian professional [[cricket]]er and a member of [[Civil Services of India#Construction|Haryana Police Service]] cadre who currently serves as [[Deputy superintendent of police]].{{what|date=August 2019}} He has made sporadic appearances for the [[Indian cricket team]].\n\n==Style of play==\nA bowling [[all rounder]], he played as a right-handed batsman and a right-arm medium-fast bowler and captained his state, [[Haryana cricket team|Haryana]].\n\n==First class==\nSharma made his first-class debut for Haryana against [[Madhya Pradesh cricket team|Madhya Pradesh]] in the 2002/03 [[Ranji Trophy]], hitting 81 before taking 11/84 to lead Haryana to a 103 run victory.<ref>{{cite web| title = Haryana vs Madhya Pradesh at Rohtak 9\u201312 November 2002| url= http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/PLATE/ROUND1/HRYNA_MP_RJI_09-12NOV2002.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> He had made his debut in the limited over domestic arena the season before.<ref name=\"profile\">{{cite web|first =Siddhartha |last= Vaidyanathan| title = Joginder Sharma| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/current/player/29976.html |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]| accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Sharma finished his debut season with 24 wickets at 17.41 and 280 runs at 46.66<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2002-03/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> He followed this with 148 runs at 68.51 and 23 wickets at 23.39 in 2003/04 Ranji season.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2003-04/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> He was selected for the [[North Zone cricket team|North Zone]] team for the [[Duleep Trophy]], and took 6/59 in a match against [[West Zone cricket team|West Zone]] during the victorious campaign.<ref>{{cite news|title = Chopra guides North Zone home| url = http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/137102.html | publisher = [[Cricinfo]] | date = 2004-02-25 |accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref>\n\n==National attention==\n\nSharma gained national attention in a match for India A against the national team at [[Bangalore]], when he dismissed [[Rahul Dravid]], [[V. V. S. Laxman]] and [[Yuvraj Singh]].<ref name =\"profile\"/><ref>{{cite news|first = Dileep | last = Premachandran| title = India A take charge despite Ganguly's effort| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/143664.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]] |date = 29 September 2004 | accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> He also played for the Rest of India side, which defeated [[Mumbai cricket team|Mumbai]] in the [[Irani Trophy]].<ref>{{cite news| title = Rest of India crush Mumbai| url=http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/india/content/story/143598.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]] |date = 25 September 2004 | accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref>\n\nHaving scored two successive centuries, and securing a 14/116 in the 2004/05 [[Ranji Trophy]] against [[Vidarbha cricket team|Vidarbha]],<ref>{{cite web| title = Vidarbha vs Haryana at Nagpur 13\u201316 December 2004| url= http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/PLATE/ROUND4/VIDAR_HRYNA_RJI_13-16DEC2004.html| publisher = [[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Sharma won his place in the Indian side for the [[Bangladeshi cricket team|Bangladesh]] tour. He had limited batting opportunities, scoring 34 in two brief knocks at the end of the innings without being dismissed, but his bowling was ineffective, taking 1/99, and was dropped after playing in that ODI series.<ref name =\"statsguruodi\"/> He ended the Ranji Trophy with 36 wickets, the second highest at 15.47 and 472 runs at 52.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Most Wickets | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/CUM-STATS//IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BOWL_MOST_WKTS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title = Batting \u2013 Most Runs | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/link_to_database/ARCHIVE/2004-05/IND_LOCAL/RANJI/STATS/CUM-STATS//IND_LOCAL_RANJI_AVS_BAT_MOST_RUNS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref> In 2005/06, he topped the Duleep Trophy bowling averages.<ref>{{cite web|title = Bowling \u2013 Best averages | url =http://aus.cricinfo.com/db/ARCHIVE/2005-06/IND_LOCAL/DULEEP/STATS/IND_LOCAL_DULEEP_AVS_BOWL_BEST_AVS.html| publisher = Cricinfo | accessdate = 2007-02-13}}</ref>\n\n==Domestic season==\n\nSharma performed strongly in the 2006/07 Indian domestic season to bring himself into contention for national selection. His batting for [[North Zone cricket team|North Zone]] in the [[Duleep Trophy]] yielded 421 runs in three matches, and he was subsequently the leading wicket-taker in the Ranji Trophy, taking 39 wickets in seven matches, as well as two ten-wicket hauls and a [[hat trick]].<ref name=\"cricinfo\">{{cite news|first = Siddhartha |last = Vaidyanathan| title = Joginder gets a second chance|url= http://content-aus.cricinfo.com/ci/content/story/276253.html|publisher = [[Cricinfo]]| date = 12 January 2007| accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Despite being unable to prevent Haryana from being relegated to the Plate division, he was recalled in January 2007 to the team at the expense of [[Irfan Pathan]] for the ODI series against the [[West Indies cricket team|West Indies]].<ref name = \"cricinfo\"/> He was selected for the second ODI in [[Cuttack]], but after scoring 1 and failing to take a wicket,<ref name=\"statsguruodi\">{{cite web|title = Statsguru \u2013 Joginder Sharma \u2013 ODIs \u2013 Innings by innings list| url = http://statserver.cricket.org/guru?sdb=player;playerid=45592;class=odiplayer;filter=basic;team=0;opposition=0;notopposition=0;season=0;homeaway=0;continent=0;country=0;notcountry=0;groundid=0;startdefault=2004-12-23;start=2004-12-23;enddefault=2007-01-24;end=2007-01-24;tourneyid=0;finals=0;daynight=0;toss=0;scheduledovers=0;scheduleddays=0;innings=0;result=0;followon=0;seriesresult=0;captain=0;keeper=0;dnp=0;recent=;viewtype=aro_list;runslow=;runshigh=;batposition=0;dismissal=0;bowposition=0;ballslow=;ballshigh=;bpof=0;overslow=;overshigh=;conclow=;conchigh=;wicketslow=;wicketshigh=;dismissalslow=;dismissalshigh=;caughtlow=;caughthigh=;caughttype=0;stumpedlow=;stumpedhigh=;csearch=;submit=1;.cgifields=viewtype |publisher=[[Cricinfo]]|accessdate = 2007-02-14}}</ref> Pathan was immediately recalled and Sharma dropped. Sharma was not named in the Indian squad for the [[2007 Cricket World Cup]]. \n\n==International Career==\n\nSharma found a place for himself in the [[2007 World Twenty20]]  in South Africa. He bowled the final over of the semi final against [[Australian cricket team|Australia]], with [[Michael Hussey]] facing and Australia needing 22 runs to win, taking two wickets as India won by 15 runs.\n\nHe also bowled the final over in the final against [[Pakistani cricket team|Pakistan]] with thirteen runs required and only one wicket in hand. His first ball went for a [[wide (cricket)|wide]] and the next was borderline but not called by the umpire. The third was a [[full toss]] which was pulled straight back over his head for six by [[Misbah-ul-Haq]]. Then he [https://www.espncricinfo.com/series/8604/commentary/287879/india-vs-pakistan-final-icc-world-twenty20-2007-08 bowled a beautiful] delivery out side off stump which Misbah attempted to [[Marillier shot|scoop]] the ball over the fine leg fielder from the fourth ball but mistimed it and was caught by [[Sreesanth]], giving India the win. The [[Government of Haryana|Haryana government]] announced a cash reward of Rs 21 lakh for Joginder Sharma in recognition of his contribution to the Indian victory.<ref>{{cite web |title = Haryana CM announces Rs.21 lakh cash reward for Joginder Sharma |url = http://www.punjabnewsline.com/content/view/5828/94/ |publisher = Punjab Newsline Network |accessdate = 2007-09-26 |url-status = dead |archiveurl = https://archive.is/20130131232544/http://www.punjabnewsline.com/content/view/5828/94/ |archivedate = 31 January 2013 |df = dmy-all }}</ref> His winning moment had earned him a job with Haryana Police. Now 13 years later, he enjoys life as a Deputy superintendent Of Police.\n\n<br />\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{India Squad 2007 Cricket World Twenty20}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Sharma, Joginder}}\n[[Category:1983 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Indian cricketers]]\n[[Category:India One Day International cricketers]]\n[[Category:India Twenty20 International cricketers]]\n[[Category:Haryana cricketers]]\n[[Category:People from Rohtak]]\n[[Category:Chennai Super Kings cricketers]]\n[[Category:North Zone cricketers]]\n[[Category:India Blue cricketers]]\n[[Category:Kolkata Knight Riders cricketers]]\n[[Category:Cricketers from Haryana]]\n", "name_user": "Harman28", "label": "safe", "comment": "Adds middle name", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Joginder_Sharma"}
{"title_page": "Richard Schlesinger (filmmaker)", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2012}}\n{{original research|date=August 2012}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=August 2012}}\n}}\n'''Richard Schlesinger''' is an American-born screenwriter, director, and producer of feature films and television.\n\nBorn and raised in Miami, Florida, he was graduated from [[Brown University]] and studied at the [[University of Paris]].\n\n==Career==\n\nOften drawn to political subjects, Schlesinger conceived and wrote the two-part Iraq War mini-series ''[[Djihad (TV series)|Djihad]]'' for Canal Plus,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fischer|first=Arnaud|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0819364/ |title=Djihad! (2006) (TV) |url-status=live |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> in France, along with director Felix Olivier. The pair also collaborated on the gritty social drama, ''[[All Night Bodega]]'', which won multiple prizes at festivals in New York, Los Angeles, Paris and Lyon.\n\nSchlesinger went to [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]] during the [[Kosovo War]] to produce the award-winning children\u2019s television series, ''[[Nashe Maalo]]'' (Our Neighborhood). Created by [[Sesame Workshop]], the half-hour drama used stories showing non-violent conflict resolution to help bridge ethnic divides among the youth of the Balkans. Schlesinger also directed the pilot episode.<ref name=\"IMDB RS1\">https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0772276/</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Schlesinger co-produced the political thriller ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]'',<ref name=\"IMDB RS\">{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0988047/ |title=IMDb Pro : Traitor Business Details |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> directed by [[Jeffrey Nachmanoff]], shot in France, Morocco and Canada. He also produced three sci-fi movies in Toronto. Titles include ''[[Descent (2005 film)|Descent]]'', ''[[Swarmed]]'', and ''[[Solar Attack]]''.\n\nSchlesinger\u2019s other producing credits include ''[[Captive (1998 film)|Captive]]'', ''[[Outlaws: The Legend of O.B. Taggart]]'', ''[[Clover (1997 film)|Clover]]'' and four TV movies for Hallmark Entertainment. He also produced the television series ''[[The Black Stallion]]'' and ''[[Crossbow (TV series)|Crossbow]]'' in France.\n\nSchlesinger directed four episodes of the series ''[[Crossbow]]'', then went on to direct [[Terence Hill]] in ''[[Lucky Luke]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecitalent.fr/biographie/richard-schlesinger |title=Richard SCHLESINGER &#124; Ecitalent |publisher=Ecitalent.fr |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> based on the French comic book character, produced for Berlusconi\u2019s ReteItalia and shot in Santa Fe, NM.\n\nSchlesinger also spent a number of years writing youth-oriented family films for Canadian producer Rock Demers\u2019 La F\u00eate Productions, including ''[[Daniel and the Superdogs]]'', ''[[Regina (film)|Regina]]'' and ''[[Summer with the Ghosts]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]'' - Co-producer\t 2008\n* ''[[Djihad (TV series)|Djihad]]'' - Writer 2006\n* ''[[Solar Attack]]'' - Executive Producer 2006\n* ''[[Swarmed]]'' - Executive Producer 2005\n* ''[[Descent (2005 film)|Descent]]'' - Executive Producer 2005\n* ''[[Daniel and the Superdogs]]'' - Writer 2004\n* ''[[Summer with the Ghosts]]'' - Writer 2004\n* ''[[All Night Bodega]]'' - Writer 2002\n* ''[[Reg\u00edna]]'' - Writer 2001\n* ''[[Nashe Maalo]]'' (''Our Neighborhood'') (series) - Producer 1999\n* ''[[Captive (1998 film)|Captive]]'' - Producer 1998\n* ''[[Clover (1997 film)|Clover]]'' - Line Producer 1997 \n* ''[[Outlaws: The Legend of O.B. Taggart]]'' - Line Producer 1994\n* ''[[Lucky Luke 2]]'' - Director 1993\n* ''[[Braxton (film)|Braxton]]'' - Producer 1989\n* ''[[Crossbow: The Movie]]'' - Line Producer 1989\n* ''[[Crossbow (TV series)|Crossbow]]'' (series) - Director/Producer 1988\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0772276}}\n*[http://ecitalent.fr/biographie/richard-schlesinger Richard Schlesinger @ ECI (Entertainment Creative Interface) Global Talent Management]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schlesinger, Richard}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2012}}\n{{original research|date=August 2012}}\n{{BLP primary sources|date=August 2012}}\n}}\n'''Richard Schlesinger''' is an American-born screenwriter, director, and producer of feature films and television.\n\nBorn and raised in Miami, Florida, he was graduated from [[Brown University]] and studied at the [[University of Paris]].\n\n==Career==\n\nOften drawn to political subjects, Schlesinger conceived and wrote the two-part Iraq War mini-series ''[[Djihad (TV series)|Djihad]]'' for Canal Plus,<ref>{{cite web|last=Fischer|first=Arnaud|url=https://www.imdb.com/title/tt0819364/ |title=Djihad! (2006) (TV) |url-status=live |accessdate=2012-08-12}}</ref> in France, along with director Felix Olivier. The pair also collaborated on the gritty social drama, ''[[All Night Bodega]]'', which won multiple prizes at festivals in New York, Los Angeles, Paris and Lyon.\n\nSchlesinger went to [[Macedonia]] during the [[Kosovo War]] to produce the award-winning children\u2019s television series, ''[[Nashe Maalo]]'' (Our Neighborhood). Created by [[Sesame Workshop]], the half-hour drama used stories showing non-violent conflict resolution to help bridge ethnic divides among the youth of the Balkans. Schlesinger also directed the pilot episode.<ref name=\"IMDB RS1\">https://www.imdb.com/name/nm0772276/</ref>\n\nIn 2008, Schlesinger co-produced the political thriller ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]'',<ref name=\"IMDB RS\">{{cite web|url=https://pro.imdb.com/title/tt0988047/ |title=IMDb Pro : Traitor Business Details |publisher=Pro.imdb.com |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> directed by [[Jeffrey Nachmanoff]], shot in France, Morocco and Canada. He also produced three sci-fi movies in Toronto. Titles include ''[[Descent (2005 film)|Descent]]'', ''[[Swarmed]]'', and ''[[Solar Attack]]''.\n\nSchlesinger\u2019s other producing credits include ''[[Captive (1998 film)|Captive]]'', ''[[Outlaws: The Legend of O.B. Taggart]]'', ''[[Clover (1997 film)|Clover]]'' and four TV movies for Hallmark Entertainment. He also produced the television series ''[[The Black Stallion]]'' and ''[[Crossbow (TV series)|Crossbow]]'' in France.\n\nSchlesinger directed four episodes of the series ''[[Crossbow]]'', then went on to direct [[Terence Hill]] in ''[[Lucky Luke]]'',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ecitalent.fr/biographie/richard-schlesinger |title=Richard SCHLESINGER &#124; Ecitalent |publisher=Ecitalent.fr |date= |accessdate=2012-08-10}}</ref> based on the French comic book character, produced for Berlusconi\u2019s ReteItalia and shot in Santa Fe, NM.\n\nSchlesinger also spent a number of years writing youth-oriented family films for Canadian producer Rock Demers\u2019 La F\u00eate Productions, including ''[[Daniel and the Superdogs]]'', ''[[Regina (film)|Regina]]'' and ''[[Summer with the Ghosts]]''.\n\n== Filmography ==\n\n* ''[[Traitor (film)|Traitor]]'' - Co-producer\t 2008\n* ''[[Djihad (TV series)|Djihad]]'' - Writer 2006\n* ''[[Solar Attack]]'' - Executive Producer 2006\n* ''[[Swarmed]]'' - Executive Producer 2005\n* ''[[Descent (2005 film)|Descent]]'' - Executive Producer 2005\n* ''[[Daniel and the Superdogs]]'' - Writer 2004\n* ''[[Summer with the Ghosts]]'' - Writer 2004\n* ''[[All Night Bodega]]'' - Writer 2002\n* ''[[Reg\u00edna]]'' - Writer 2001\n* ''[[Nashe Maalo]]'' (''Our Neighborhood'') (series) - Producer 1999\n* ''[[Captive (1998 film)|Captive]]'' - Producer 1998\n* ''[[Clover (1997 film)|Clover]]'' - Line Producer 1997 \n* ''[[Outlaws: The Legend of O.B. Taggart]]'' - Line Producer 1994\n* ''[[Lucky Luke 2]]'' - Director 1993\n* ''[[Braxton (film)|Braxton]]'' - Producer 1989\n* ''[[Crossbow: The Movie]]'' - Line Producer 1989\n* ''[[Crossbow (TV series)|Crossbow]]'' (series) - Director/Producer 1988\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n*{{IMDb name|0772276}}\n*[http://ecitalent.fr/biographie/richard-schlesinger Richard Schlesinger @ ECI (Entertainment Creative Interface) Global Talent Management]\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Schlesinger, Richard}}\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:American film directors]]\n[[Category:American film producers]]\n[[Category:Brown University alumni]]\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMacedonia(link changed toNorth Macedonia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Richard_Schlesinger_(filmmaker)"}
{"title_page": "Church of the Ascension of Jesus, Skopje", "text_new": "{{short description|Macedonian Orthodox Church in Skopje, North Macedonia}}\n[[File:Sv Spas.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Entrance to the church courtyard]]\n[[File:Goce Del\u010dev sarkofag.JPG|thumb|200px|right|The sarcophagus of [[Gotse Delchev]]]]\n[[File:Crkva Sv. Spas, Skopje.jpg|thumb|Historical images of Skopje: Church of the Ascension of Jesus, Skopje]]\n\n'''The Church of the Ascension of Jesus''' ({{Macedonian|\u0426\u044a\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u201e\u0421\u0432. \u0421\u043f\u0430\u0441\u201c}}) is a [[Macedonian Orthodox Church \u2013 Ohrid Archbishopric|Macedonian Orthodox Church]] in [[Skopje]], [[North Macedonia|Macedonia]]. It is situated east of [[Kale Fortress]].\n\nThe church was built in the mid-16th century<ref>[http://www.soros.org.mk/konkurs/076/makver/crkva_svspas.html www.soros.org.mk, Crkva Sveti Spas, Skopje]{{in lang|mk}}</ref> and is three-nave, with the middle vessel arched and flat pages covered with gains in domes. In the west is the gallery for women. On the south wall, above the present level of the floor during the repair of the church year 1963-64 was discovered a flat painting dating from the 16th-17th century. During the 19th century the church was given the inal look. In 1824 the iconostasis was completed and in 1867 it was part of the throne icons. The iconostasis and icons were made by cooperatives and traders from Skopje. \n\nThe Orthodox congregation under Ottomans was included in a specific community under Greek domination. With the rise of nationalism, the Bulgarian population of the area voted in 1874 overwhelmingly, by 91% in favour of joining the [[Bulgarian Exarchate]].<ref>\u0426\u044a\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0446\u044a\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0432 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0422\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u0441\u043a\u0438, \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442, \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, 2003 \u0433. \u0441\u0442\u0440. 219.</ref> This remained so until 1890 when it was taken back by the Greek priests. In 1901 the church was taken from the Serb community and became the seat of the Skopje Metropolitan, [[Firmilijan Dra\u017ei\u0107|Firmilijan]] and his successors.<ref>N. Makuljevi\u0107, ''Umetnost i nacionalna ideja u 19. veku'', Belgrade 2006, p. 321</ref>\n\nThe door for entering in the yard is heavy and made from [[oak]]. In the yard is a white [[sarcophagus]] containing the remains of the Bulgarian revolutionary [[Gotse Delchev]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Church of the Ascension of Christ (Skopje)}}\n{{coord|42|00|03|N|21|26|09|E|type:landmark_region:FR_source:frwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Old Bazaar, Skopje}}\n{{Skopje}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox church buildings in North Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Macedonian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Skopje]]\n[[Category:Old Bazaar, Skopje]]\n\n{{RMacedonia-church-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Macedonian Orthodox Church in Skopje, North Macedonia}}\n[[File:Sv Spas.jpg|thumb|200px|right|Entrance to the church courtyard]]\n[[File:Goce Del\u010dev sarkofag.JPG|thumb|200px|right|The sarcophagus of [[Gotse Delchev]]]]\n[[File:Crkva Sv. Spas, Skopje.jpg|thumb|Historical images of Skopje: Church of the Ascension of Jesus, Skopje]]\n\n'''The Church of the Ascension of Jesus''' ({{Macedonian|\u0426\u044a\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u201e\u0421\u0432. \u0421\u043f\u0430\u0441\u201c}}) is a [[Macedonian Orthodox Church \u2013 Ohrid Archbishopric|Macedonian Orthodox Church]] in [[Skopje]], [[Macedonia]]. It is situated east of [[Kale Fortress]].\n\nThe church was built in the mid-16th century<ref>[http://www.soros.org.mk/konkurs/076/makver/crkva_svspas.html www.soros.org.mk, Crkva Sveti Spas, Skopje]{{in lang|mk}}</ref> and is three-nave, with the middle vessel arched and flat pages covered with gains in domes. In the west is the gallery for women. On the south wall, above the present level of the floor during the repair of the church year 1963-64 was discovered a flat painting dating from the 16th-17th century. During the 19th century the church was given the inal look. In 1824 the iconostasis was completed and in 1867 it was part of the throne icons. The iconostasis and icons were made by cooperatives and traders from Skopje. \n\nThe Orthodox congregation under Ottomans was included in a specific community under Greek domination. With the rise of nationalism, the Bulgarian population of the area voted in 1874 overwhelmingly, by 91% in favour of joining the [[Bulgarian Exarchate]].<ref>\u0426\u044a\u0440\u043a\u0432\u0430 \u0438 \u0446\u044a\u0440\u043a\u043e\u0432\u0435\u043d \u0436\u0438\u0432\u043e\u0442 \u0432 \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0438\u044f, \u041f\u0435\u0442\u044a\u0440 \u041f\u0435\u0442\u0440\u043e\u0432, \u0425\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e \u0422\u0435\u043c\u0435\u043b\u0441\u043a\u0438, \u041c\u0430\u043a\u0435\u0434\u043e\u043d\u0441\u043a\u0438 \u041d\u0430\u0443\u0447\u0435\u043d \u0418\u043d\u0441\u0442\u0438\u0442\u0443\u0442, \u0421\u043e\u0444\u0438\u044f, 2003 \u0433. \u0441\u0442\u0440. 219.</ref> This remained so until 1890 when it was taken back by the Greek priests. In 1901 the church was taken from the Serb community and became the seat of the Skopje Metropolitan, [[Firmilijan Dra\u017ei\u0107|Firmilijan]] and his successors.<ref>N. Makuljevi\u0107, ''Umetnost i nacionalna ideja u 19. veku'', Belgrade 2006, p. 321</ref>\n\nThe door for entering in the yard is heavy and made from [[oak]]. In the yard is a white [[sarcophagus]] containing the remains of the Bulgarian revolutionary [[Gotse Delchev]].\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commonscat|Church of the Ascension of Christ (Skopje)}}\n{{coord|42|00|03|N|21|26|09|E|type:landmark_region:FR_source:frwiki|display=title}}\n\n{{Old Bazaar, Skopje}}\n{{Skopje}}\n\n[[Category:Eastern Orthodox church buildings in North Macedonia]]\n[[Category:Macedonian Orthodox Church]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures in Skopje]]\n[[Category:Old Bazaar, Skopje]]\n\n{{RMacedonia-church-stub}}\n", "name_user": "R'n'B", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toMacedonia(link changed toNorth Macedonia) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Church_of_the_Ascension_of_Jesus,_Skopje"}
